[2]
Date: Thu, 2 Feb 2006 10:09:59 +0100
From: Dr. Burkhard Rieke <Burkhard.Rieke@crm.de>

Concerning the 3 exposures reported, considered to be associated with
the same cat, how was the time interval between exposures? For a
non-veterinarian, it is difficult to judge the many "rules of thumb"
circulating about survival times of infected animals. Would an
observation time of, say, 5 days post-bite be enough to rule out
rabies in the cat, if it survives? Or rule out being infectious at
the time of the bite? This one was killed and found out to be rabid,
in which case there are no [questions]. But imagine those killed and
not found rabid.
--
Dr. Burkhard Rieke
MD, DTM&H (Liv.)
Internal Medicine, Tropical Medicine
Centre for Travel Medicine
Hansaallee 321
40549 Dusseldorf, Germany
<rieke@crm.de>

[I tried to obtain some up-to-date information on rabies in Tennessee:
CDC Rabies Epidemiology Page
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/rabies/Epidemiology/Epidemiology.htm>
Statistics up to 2001; some data on 2002. Shows TN at risk of skunk
rabies; raccoon rabies is in the Carolinas to the east.
TN Dept of Health ... only an information sheet on rabies, but
<http://www2.state.tn.us/health/CEDS/WebAim/interactive.htm
Communicable & Environmental Disease Statistics: one human case in
2002 (data only available up to 2003)
TN Dept of Agriculture, Animal Health: Not very informative, but
there was an 1 Oct 2005 Newsletter (vol 1, issue 1) posted
<http://www.state.tn.us/agriculture/regulate/animals/newsletter.pdf
So taking advantage of professorial privilege, I contacted an ex-grad
student, Dr. John Dunn, Assistant State Public Health Veterinarian,
TN Dept of Health, for an informed update on the rabies situation in
Tennessee, which follows. - Mod.MHJ]
