[3]
Date: Fri 3 Feb 2006 11:09 AM
From: John Dunn <John.Dunn@state.tn.us>

The Tennessee SHD, East and Northeast Regional Offices conducted
rabies testing and provided consultation following the human
exposures to the rabid cat subsequently reported in ProMED-mail
(Rabies, feline, human exposure - USA (TN) 20060201.0326).
The 2 exposure incidents occurred on consecutive days, 13 and 14 Jan
2006, approximately 3 blocks apart. Testing in the state public
health laboratory indicated that the cat (no vaccination history, no
owner identified) was infected with raccoon variant rabies.
Tennessee has had long-standing bat rabies and endemic terrestrial
skunk rabies. In 2003, raccoon variant rabies was first documented in
northeastern Tennessee as part of the expanding raccoon rabies
epizootic in the eastern US (See 2004 rabies maps,
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/rabies/professional/publications/Surveillance/Surveillance04/RabSlideSet2004.ppt>).
The recent human exposures to the rabid cat highlight a couple of
important aspects of rabies surveillance and control in TN.
Surveillance activities for rabies in southeastern and eastern border
counties, where raccoon rabies is spreading, has been enhanced
through submission of animals to the TN SHD and USDA-Wildlife
Services. Additionally, from 2002 to present, Tennessee has conducted
the Oral Rabies Vaccination (ORV) program in collaboration with CDC
and USDA-WS (<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/ws/rabies/orv/dist/tn.html>)
in an effort to control the westward spread of raccoon rabies into
TN. In addition to public health measures targeting animal control,
vaccination of domestic animals, and education of the public
regarding rabies risks and wildlife rabies, expanding the USDA-WS ORV
program will be important in slowing the spread of raccoon rabies
into Tennessee and reducing human rabies exposures.
--
John R. Dunn, DVM, PhD
Medical Epidemiologist
Tennessee Department of Health
Communicable and Environmental Disease Services
4th Floor, Cordell Hull Bldg.
425 5th Ave. North
Nashville, TN 37247-4911
<John.Dunn@state.tn.us>
[John, thank you. - Mod.MHJ]
